  <h1>ARIA - Accessible Rich Internet Application</h1>

  <p>ARIA (Accessible Rich Internet Applications) is a set of attributes that can be added to HTML elements to improve the accessibility of web content, particularly for users with disabilities.</p>

  <h2>Key Concepts:</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Roles:</strong> ARIA defines roles for elements such as buttons, links, menus, and more, to describe their purpose or function.</li>
    <li><strong>States:</strong> ARIA states describe the current condition or status of an element, such as expanded, selected, or disabled.</li>
    <li><strong>Properties:</strong> ARIA properties provide additional information about elements, such as labels, descriptions, or values.</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Example Usage:</h2>

  <p>Below are examples demonstrating the usage of ARIA attributes:</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Element</th>
        <th>ARIA Attributes</th>
        <th>Description</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Button</td>
        <td>role="button"</td>
        <td><button role="button">Click me</button></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Link</td>
        <td>role="link"</td>
        <td><a href="#" role="link">Visit website</a></td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Menu</td>
        <td>role="menu"</td>
        <td>
          <ul role="menu">
            <li>Option 1</li>
            <li>Option 2</li>
            <li>Option 3</li>
          </ul>
        </td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

